{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85c3d286-a240-4f8c-890c-bb75cbfe809c","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple crash reports** rather than .NET-style core dumps:\n\n1. **Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` or `.crash`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, Apple's `.ips` crash reports include the faulting thread's stack trace with native symbols, which is usually the most useful starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"689538a7-20f1-4ed2-a233-451f13d45e2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":268,"requestId":"AC12:26F840:13930D9:16066D8:6A067165"},"id":"73920692-d6e5-474f-9f22-448d950147ba","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:48.928Z","parentId":"fac96385-01f7-4ed4-adaa-f063840886ed"}
